  <h1>
   ptr
  </h1>
  This function will attempt to convert a given value into a pointer data type, where the value
  <i>
   must
  </i>
  be either a
  <span>
   real
  </span>
  , a
  <span>
   string
  </span>
  , an
  <span>
   int64
  </span>
  , an
  <span>
   int32
  </span>
  , or a
  <span>
   ptr
  </span>
  . Anything else will cause the game to crash with an error message.
  <h4>
   Syntax:
  </h4>
  <pre><code class="language-gml">ptr(n);
</code></pre>
  <table>
   <tbody>
    <tr>
     <th>
      Argument
     </th>
     <th>
      Type
     </th>
     <th>
      Description
     </th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
     <td>
      n
     </td>
     <td>
      <span>
       <a href="../../../../GameMaker_Language/GML_Overview/Data_Types.htm">
        Real
       </a>
      </span>
      ,
      <span>
       <a href="../../../../GameMaker_Language/GML_Overview/Data_Types.htm">
        String
       </a>
      </span>
      , or
      <span>
       <a href="../../../../GameMaker_Language/GML_Overview/Data_Types.htm">
        Pointer
       </a>
      </span>
     </td>
     <td>
      The value to convert.
     </td>
    </tr>
   </tbody>
  </table>
  <h4>
   Returns:
  </h4>
  <pre><code class="language-gml"><a href="../../../../GameMaker_Language/GML_Overview/Data_Types.htm">
 Pointer
</a></code></pre>
  <h4>
   <b>
    Example:
   </b>
  </h4>
  <pre><code class="language-gml">if !is_ptr(val)
{
    val = ptr(application_surface);
}
</code></pre>
  The above code checks the variable "val" to see if it contains a pointer and if it does not then one is assigned to it.
